    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Convert Excel to PDF</h2>
      <p>
        Click the file input and select an .xlsx spreadsheet from your computer. The tool reads the file entirely within your browser, parses the internal ZIP and XML structure, and extracts the cell values from the first worksheet. A spreadsheet-style preview appears so you can verify the data looks correct before converting. If your first row contains column headers, keep the "First row is header" checkbox enabled so the PDF renders that row with a distinct blue background and bold white text.
      </p>
      <p>
        Once you are satisfied with the preview, click "Download PDF" to generate and save the file. The PDF renders your spreadsheet data as a properly formatted table with alternating row shading, cell borders, and automatic column sizing. The result is a clean, print-ready document that anyone can open without needing Excel or any other spreadsheet application.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Why Convert Excel to PDF</h2>
      <p>
        Sharing spreadsheet data often creates friction. Not everyone has Microsoft Excel installed, and even those who do may have a different version that renders the file differently. Google Sheets can open .xlsx files but sometimes misinterprets formatting or formulas. By converting to PDF, you create a universally readable document that looks identical on every device and operating system. The recipient does not need any specialized software because PDF readers are built into every modern web browser, phone, and tablet.
      </p>
      <p>
        PDF conversion is particularly valuable when you need to distribute financial reports, project status updates, inventory lists, or any tabular data to stakeholders who should see the information but should not modify it. A PDF preserves the exact layout you intended while preventing accidental edits. It is also the preferred format for email attachments in professional settings because the recipient knows the document will display correctly regardless of their platform.
      </p>

      <h3>How the PDF Is Generated</h3>
      <p>
        The tool constructs a valid PDF 1.4 document entirely in JavaScript. It creates the page structure, embeds the standard Helvetica and Helvetica-Bold fonts, and renders your data row by row into a formatted table. Header rows get a blue background with white text. Data rows alternate between white and light gray for readability. Cell borders and column separators keep the data visually organized. The resulting file opens correctly in Adobe Acrobat, browser PDF viewers, Preview on macOS, and every other standards-compliant PDF reader.
      </p>

      <h3>What About Formulas and Formatting?</h3>
      <p>
        The converter extracts the last calculated values from formula cells, not the formulas themselves. A cell containing <code>=SUM(A1:A10)</code> will appear in the PDF as the numeric result that Excel computed when the file was last saved. Cell-level formatting such as custom colors, fonts, conditional formatting rules, and merged cells are not transferred to the PDF. The tool focuses on data fidelity: every value from your spreadsheet appears in the PDF table exactly as stored in the worksheet XML.
      </p>

      <h3>Limitations</h3>
      <p>
        The converter reads the first worksheet in the workbook. Multi-sheet workbooks will only produce a PDF from Sheet 1. Date values stored as Excel serial numbers appear as raw numbers because date formatting information lives in the styles XML, which is separate from cell values. Charts, images, and pivot tables embedded in the spreadsheet are not included in the PDF output. For documents requiring those elements, a desktop application with full Excel rendering would be more appropriate.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How does this Excel to PDF converter work?</h3>
      <p>
        The tool reads the .xlsx file as a ZIP archive in your browser, decompresses the XML files inside, parses the worksheet structure, extracts cell values, and renders them as a formatted table in a PDF document. No data is sent to any server.
      </p>

      <h3>Will my spreadsheet data be uploaded to a server?</h3>
      <p>
        No. Everything happens locally in your browser. Your data never leaves your device. You can disconnect from the internet and the tool still works.
      </p>

      <h3>Does the PDF preserve Excel formatting?</h3>
      <p>
        The tool renders a clean table with header highlighting and alternating row shading. Custom cell formatting like fonts, colors, and conditional formatting from the original file is not carried over.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I mark the first row as a header?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Check the "First row is header" box before downloading. The header row will appear with a blue background and bold white text in the PDF.
      </p>

      <h3>Is there a file size or row limit?</h3>
      <p>
        Processing happens in browser memory. Spreadsheets with thousands of rows convert without issues on modern devices. For very large files exceeding 50,000 rows, a desktop tool may be more practical.
      </p>

